curam.util.client.domain.marshal

Class DateTimeMarshal

  • java.lang.Object
    • curam.util.common.plugin.AbstractPlugIn
      • curam.util.common.domain.AbstractDomainPlugIn
        • curam.util.client.domain.marshal.AbstractDomainMarshal
          • curam.util.client.domain.marshal.DateTimeMarshal
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    DomainMarshal, DomainPlugIn, PlugIn

    public class DateTimeMarshal
extends AbstractDomainMarshal

    A domain marshal for date time types. Date times contain values that represent a date and time. The date format is determined by the SVR_DATETIME domain. The date time format is a date and time value separated by a space character. The time value returned by the client will correspond to the current time format set for the application.

    Configuration

    The following configuration properties must be set:

    • date-domain: The domain to use when formatting the date part of the date-time value. It is a current technical limitation that the date-time domain itself cannot be used, so a surrogate domain is required.
    • time-domain: The domain to use when formatting the time part of the date-time value. It is a current technical limitation that the date-time domain itself cannot be used, so a surrogate domain is required.

      • preResolve

        public java.lang.Object preResolve(java.lang.String data)
                            throws MarshalException
        Initializes a value for before paths are resolved. For complex domains, the "get" methods may be called several times, so it could be inefficient if they had to parse the data every time they had to resolve a value embedded in it. This method allows the marshal to perform this kind of preparatory processing once and to create an object that will be more suitable for use by the "get" methods. Any object can be returned, or the value string itself can be returned. The object will be passed to one of the "get" methods each time a path is resolved.

        This implementation just returns the data string without changes.

        Specified by:
        preResolve in interface DomainMarshal
        Overrides:
        preResolve in class AbstractDomainMarshal
        Parameters:
        data - The string value to be prepared. This is the value that has been formatted by the converter.
        Returns:
        The object that will be passed to a "get" method when paths are resolved.
        Throws:
        MarshalException - If there is an error preparing the data.

      • get

        public java.lang.String get(java.lang.Object data,
                            Path path)
                     throws MarshalException

        Gets the value from the data identified by the specified path.

        This marshal supports paths of the following forms:

        • /date - returns the date information.
        • /time - returns the time information.
        Parameters:
        data - the complete data value that requires un-assembling.
        path - this means of identifying the value to be retrieved from data.
        Returns:
        the part of data identified by the specified path
        Throws:
        MarshalException - identifying any marshaling problems.

      • acceptConfiguration

        public boolean acceptConfiguration()
                            throws PlugInException
        Indicates if the plug-in will accept its configuration. It is up to the plug-in to decide what configuration it will accept. The configuration is accessible via the other methods on this interface. This method is called by the system only once when the plug-in is loaded and configured. The system will not start until all of the plug-ins accept their configurations, so this method allows the other methods on this plug-in to be written with the minimum of safety checks.

        This implementation accepts all configurations without any checks.

        The configuration is accepted if the "date-domain" and "time-domain" properties are set. The domain names are not checked for validity, only that they are not null or empty.

        Specified by:
        acceptConfiguration in interface PlugIn
        Overrides:
        acceptConfiguration in class AbstractPlugIn
        Returns:
        true if the plug-in will accept its configuration, false otherwise. If false, an error will be reported by the system.
        Throws:
        PlugInException - If the reason for the rejection of the configuration is complex and a more specific exception message would make it easier to determine how to remedy the problem, an exception may be thrown instead of returning false.
